# UI testability (Playwright + a11y)

When adding or editing **HTML templates**, include hooks so Playwright (and similar tools) can target stable nodes, and keep the accessibility tree meaningful.

## data-testid

- Add **`data-testid`** on meaningful regions and controls: app shell sections, toolbars, primary buttons, canvas/viewport wrappers, selection handles, upload zones, etc.
- Use **kebab-case**, namespaced names (e.g. `canvas-handle-rotate`, `tool-selector`, `editor-canvas-area`) so IDs stay unique and readable.
- Prefer test ids over brittle selectors (CSS classes used only for styling, or dynamic SVG structure alone).

## ARIA and semantics

- Add **`aria-label`** (or `aria-labelledby` / visible text) where control purpose isn’t obvious from visible text alone.
- Use **`aria-hidden="true"`** on decorative-only UI (e.g. ruler chrome, purely visual overlay chrome) so snapshots stay focused on real controls.
- For toolbar **toggle** tools, use **`[attr.aria-pressed]`** (or appropriate `role` / `aria-checked`) so pressed state is exposed.
- Don’t duplicate: if a visible label is enough, you don’t need a redundant `aria-label`.

## Inline templates

If markup lives in a component’s **inline `template:`** string (e.g. `app.ts`), apply the same conventions there as in `*.html` files.

## Playwright usage

These attributes pair with **`page.getByTestId('…')`** and accessibility-based queries (`getByRole`, `getByLabel`), including Playwright MCP snapshots.
